<hr>
<i>Posted by Crydee Ossiriand on 10-26-2001 09:19 PM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/Shy_Face.gif" alt="" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p>/em grumbles at friends who keep dragging me back to answer questions...<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>I wonder though, shouldnt the treant have given a message when the guy turned something in? like "havent you forgot something..." Wonder if you saw that message.</b><br />
<br />
This is not the case with Xanuusus. He's one of the NPCs that says nothing untill all of the correct items are turned in. Many epic NPCs are like this. Niklas hit it right as to why Verant doesn't support Multiquesting, and I honesly have to agree with them on it. While I believe the feature should remain, there is always some level of risk involved with it.<br />
<br />
<HR><br />
<br />
My general advise in regards to multiquestings is to know who you are doing it with. Although it probably is really obvious for some, I think it needs to be stated due to cases like this.<br />
<br />
<br />
Preferably you should only do MQs with someone you know and trust or someone that is referred to you by someone you trust. For example, Crydee's in-game big brother MQed the sky sphere to him. I think I could trust my character's big brother not to cheat me.<br />
<br />
<br />
If you're buying a MQ, always keep in mind what guild the person is with first and foremost. Oftentimes such loot is considered guild property, so contacting an officer of that guild [or whoever their official guild loot selling person is] is a better way to get to ensure a proper MQ than some random indivudal. The more merchant oriented guilds that love to make money off of selling MQs tend to be very reliable as they will loose all their customers if they start cheating people though you will pay a lot going this route.<br />
<br />
If the person is unguilded, it's probably best to just pass on the deal. Unless it is an unguilded individual who is well-known throughout the server to be a good person. In that case, you are probably safe - unless the character has been ebayed.<br />
<br />
If the person is with a guild that has a bad server reputation, just run away.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
/VacationMode on<FONT face="arial, helvetica" size="2"><br>
